From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: pai-nix <pai-nix@localhost>
Date: Sat, 2 May 2026 17:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 5/5] Fix validator spurious failures on NixOS

After patches 0001 and 0004 land, the post-install validator still reports
two false failures on a working NixOS install:

  1. "PAI core skill — Not found — clone PAI repo to enable"
     The check (validate.ts:177) tests `~/.claude/skills/PAI/SKILL.md`,
     which the PAI v5.0.0 release does not ship — the release contains 46
     skills (Agents, Aphorisms, … PAIUpgrade, … WriteStory) but no bare
     `PAI` skill folder. The check is testing for an artifact that the
     upstream release does not produce. Likely a pre-v5.0 vestige from
     when there was a "PAI core" skill that was renamed/removed.

     Fix: replace the check with a "Core skill set" probe that verifies
     four cognitive primitives — ContextSearch, Knowledge, ISA, Interview
     — each have a SKILL.md present. Failure is now informative (names
     which core skill is missing) instead of advising to "clone PAI repo
     to enable" on a packaged install where the repo content IS the
     package.

  2. "Shell alias (pai) — Not found — run: source ~/.zshrc"
     Patch 0004 already wraps the alias check (and several adjacent
     install-flow branches) in `if (process.env.NIX_STORE)` to skip
     them on NixOS. But `$NIX_STORE` is set ONLY during `nix-build`
     derivation execution — Nix does NOT set it in the user-shell
     runtime environment. `printenv NIX_STORE` on a NixOS user session
     returns empty even though NIX_PROFILES, NIX_PATH, and NIX_LD are
     present. The 0004 guard checks a build-time signal at runtime and
     therefore always falls through to the non-NixOS branch.

     Fix: replace every `process.env.NIX_STORE` (and `${NIX_STORE:-}`
     in shell scripts) with `process.env.PAI_NIX_INSTALL` /
     `${PAI_NIX_INSTALL:-}`. The Nix wrapper (default.nix installPhase)
     exports `PAI_NIX_INSTALL=1` before invoking install.sh, so the
     marker is deterministic, package-owned, and visible to every
     sub-process. Replaces a build-time inference with an explicit
     runtime contract.

Files touched (paths relative to upstream source root):
  Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/install.sh                                   (2)
  Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PAI-Install/cli/index.ts                 (2)
  Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PAI-Install/engine/validate.ts           (2)
  Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PAI-Install/engine/actions.ts            (1)

The companion change — `export PAI_NIX_INSTALL=1` in the wrapper — lives
in `default.nix` (not patched, the wrapper is generated by the Nix
derivation, not part of upstream).

---
--- a/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/install.sh
+++ b/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/install.sh
@@ -149,7 +149,7 @@
 # On NixOS/Nix, bun is provided by the package manager and already on PATH
 # via the wrapper. Skip symlink creation and shell rc modifications — they
 # are unnecessary and would pollute the user's environment.
-if [ -z "${NIX_STORE:-}" ] && [ -x "$HOME/.bun/bin/bun" ]; then
+if [ -z "${PAI_NIX_INSTALL:-}" ] && [ -x "$HOME/.bun/bin/bun" ]; then
   # System-wide symlink. Try writable target first; sudo only if needed.
   for target in /usr/local/bin /opt/homebrew/bin; do
     if [ -d "$target" ] && [ -w "$target" ] && [ ! -e "$target/bun" ]; then
@@ -260,7 +260,7 @@
   echo ""
   # On NixOS/Nix, the wrapper handles post-install launch — skip the
   # interactive shell handoff that would block the wrapper from continuing.
-  if [ -n "${NIX_STORE:-}" ]; then
+  if [ -n "${PAI_NIX_INSTALL:-}" ]; then
     success "Install complete."
   elif [ -r /dev/tty ]; then
     info "Launching pai..."
